"Traverso A., Massardo A.F., Santarelli M., Call M.","A new generalized carbon exergy tax: An effective rule to control global warming",2003,"Journal of Engineering for Gas Turbines and Power","125","4",,"972","978",,,10.1115/1.1610013,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0346331514&partnerID=40&md5=f95c72837aa854deea2510dd8de4e2e0","Thermochemical Power Group, Dipartimento di Macchine, Universita di Genova, Italy, Geneva 16145, Italy; Dipartimento di Energetica, Politecnico di Torino, Torino, Italy","Traverso, A., Thermochemical Power Group, Dipartimento di Macchine, Universita di Genova, Italy, Geneva 16145, Italy; Massardo, A.F., Thermochemical Power Group, Dipartimento di Macchine, Universita di Genova, Italy, Geneva 16145, Italy; Santarelli, M., Dipartimento di Energetica, Politecnico di Torino, Torino, Italy; Call, M., Dipartimento di Energetica, Politecnico di Torino, Torino, Italy","An instrument for promoting CO2 emission reductions, taking the Kyoto Protocol goal into account, could be the assignment to energy conversion plants of a monetary charge linked to their specific emission intensity, usually called carbon tax. There are two main problems closely connected with this approach: the estimation of the charge (that must be related to the ""external"" cost associated with CO2 emission) and the choice of the strategy to determine the amount of the imposed charge. In this paper an analytical procedure proposed by the authors and called carbon exergy tax (CET) for the evaluation of CO2 emission externalities is presented. It is based on the thermoeconomic analysis of energy systems, which allows second law losses to be quantified in monetary terms: the resulting cost represents the taxation that is to be applied to the energy system under examination, calculated without any arbitrary assumption. Since the complete procedure of the CET evaluation is too complex to become a feasible instrument of energy policy, hereby, after applying the procedure to some conventional and advanced power plants, gas, oil, and coal-fueled, a new generalized approach, based on the results of the complete CET procedure, is proposed. The generalized CET evaluation requires much less information about the energy system and thus a simple and effective energy policy rule to manage global warming is obtained and available.",,"Carbon dioxide; Costs; Energy conversion; Energy policy; Global warming; Particulate emissions; Strategic planning; Taxation; Carbon energy tax (CET); Energy systems; Kyoto Protocol; Carbon; emission control",,,,,,"(1994) Managing the environment: The role of economic instruments, , Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, Paris; Goodstein, E.S., (1999) Economics and the Environment, , Prentice-Hall, Englewood Cliffs, NJ; Parkin, M., Powell, M., Matthews, K., (1997) Economics, , Addison-Wesley, Reading, MA; Borchiellini, R., Massardo, A.F., Santarelli, M., An analytical procedure for the carbon tax evaluation (2000) Energy Convers. Manage., 41. , Sept; Borchiellini, R., Massardo, A.F., Santarelli, M., A carbon tax Evaluation based on the efficient use of energy Resources (2000) Int. J. Appl. Thermodyn., 3 (3), pp. 129-145; Santarelli, M., (1998) Considerazioni Termodinamiche, Economiche Ed Ambientali Nella Analisi Ed Ottimizzazione Di Sistemi Energetici, , Ph.D. thesis, Dipartimento di Energetica, Politecnico di Torino, Torino, Italy; Santarelli, M., Borchiellini, R., Massardo, A.F., Environomic optimization for combined plants including CO2 influence (1999) IGTI Turbo Ekpo '99, , Indianapolis, IN, June, ASME, New York; Santarelli, M., Traverso, A., Cali, M., Massardo, A.F., (2001) La Metodologia dell'Efficiency Penalty Quale Criterio Termoeconomico di Penalizzazione delle Emissioni di CO2,"" X Convegno Tecnologie E Sistemi Energetici Complessi ""Sergio Stecco,"" Geneva; Massardo, A.F., Santarelli, M., Borchiellini, R., Carbon energy tax (CET): Impact on conventional energy systems design and it